						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">There are other ways of calculating the hypotenuse, as long as the angle is found first. Both h = b/sin(a) and h = c/cos(a) work, and are probably faster than 2 squares and a square root.</div>
<br />Well the big advantage of square and roots is that you can keep it to all whole numbers at all times, the only exeption is at the root part, but the algorithm on 6502.org returns the lower bounds of whole number with a remaining (that I just discard). That way you only work with whole number and saves the headaches fixed points brings with sin and cos functions brings (unless you only want to deal with $ff, $00, and $01 values, which I don't think you would because it would be really bad aproximations).</div>

					
